  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Preface to the Later Collection of Minister Lee
  author: Lee Ham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I, the son Ham, humbly record this.

    My father left behind many writings throughout his life. Yet he was not one to carefully gather and preserve them. Others took his works and never returned them, and some were destroyed by fire. In the earlier collection, there is mention of burned manuscripts, with only two or three of every ten surviving. This made compilation exceedingly difficult.

    I searched diligently among all the temples and homes of literati my father had visited, and among the circles of officials and scholars with whom he had associated. I recovered poems and prose of various kinds, which I divided into forty-one volumes for the earlier collection. Vice Minister Lee Su wrote its preface.

    After the earlier collection was completed, I discovered additional lost works and recent compositions—eight hundred forty-seven poems in regulated verse and fifty miscellaneous pieces. These became the later collection of twelve volumes.

    Alas, had misfortune prevented these works from reaching posterity, they would still serve as treasured family heirlooms for my descendants.

    When my father first achieved his degree, he once traveled with four or five fellow graduates to tour a temple, where they sang and composed verses together. One couplet from my father's poem reads:

    In the shadow of a limping donkey, blue mountains grow dim with evening;
    Among trees burning scarlet, wild geese cry as autumn deepens.

    Though it was part of a four-line form, three lines have been lost. I have heard this poem traveled to Song and was greatly treasured by their chancellor. And this was but a single composition from his youth! If even this fragment found such praise, what might they say had they seen his complete works?

    Moreover, when I composed a memorial on behalf of Scholar Qin expressing his reluctance to accept office, it contained these lines:

    Once holding paired offices as scholar,
    Many mocked him for overreaching so;
    Now he bears three great ranks together—
    Where would you place virtue now?

    These too are beloved by readers, yet the complete piece remains scattered. This too is a sorrow to bear.

    Looking at this pattern, the lost pearls and hidden jade that remain unseen are surely far more than these.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'limping donkey' refers to modest, humble travel, while 'wild geese' traditionally symbolize separation and the passage of time—both images common in farewell poetry.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to Song (the Northern Song Dynasty, 960-1279) suggests Lee Ham's father lived during or shortly before this period, indicating significant literary reputation that crossed national boundaries.
  - key: ''
    value: The memorial on accepting office reflects the Confucian tension between desire for official service and the virtue of declining improper advancement.
